                    <head>Nicholas of Lyra, Commentaries on Matthew and John</head>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <p>
                                        <locusGrp>
                                            <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                            <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                        </locusGrp>
                                        <note>The right flyleaf is foliated <locus from="120" to="120" scheme="folios"/> and consists of a leaf with random glosses by the same hand as the main text.</note>
                                        <material>Parchment</material>
                                        <dimensions type="leaf">
                                            <height quantity="295" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="210" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                    </p>
                                </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure type="leftFlyleaves" unit="folios"/>
                                    <measure type="rightFlyleaves" unit="folios"/>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil. <secFol>regna mundi</secFol>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <formula>1-11(10), 12(12, lacks 10-12)</formula>
                                    <p>
                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/66b0a2845d6968000145e133/viewOnly">Viscoll collation</ref>
                                    </p>
                                    <signatures>Quire signatures on quire 1 and 3. </signatures>
                                    <catchwords>Catchwords in brown ink, missing on quires 7 and 9.</catchwords>
                                </collation>
                                <condition>
                                    <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> torn or cut, only about half of it remains. This leaf was probably originally part of the textblock. <locus from="120" to="120" scheme="folios"/> is glued to the right cover.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner, National Library book label; upper part of page in ink by a medieval hand: <quote> attinet</quote>(page, inlcuding first words, cropped); in brown ink by a modern hand: <quote>Tillhör Bernhard Rosenblad</quote>; below, by the same hand: <quote>Köpt i December 1830 i Leipzig för 3 Rles? 16 fr. Conv. Mynt utom Kostnader</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Red leather over wooden boards. Spine painted grey. 4 double raised bands and endbands. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, in black ink or paint: <quote>Nicol. de Lyra.</quote>; in lead: M8?; stamped in gold: <quote>A 157</quote>; in red paint on a dark grey background: <quote>A</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="300" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="220" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="50" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Simple painted decoration consisting of a panel with an x-shape inside on both covers.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Cover extremely worn. The colour of the leather is heavily faded. There are multiple worm holes and abrasions on the covers. Holes from corner and centre pieces on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>, the latter also has holes after straps. Upper part of <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, remnats of label with part of a letter visible. The boards are exposed on all sides. On <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> two of the attachment straps are visible. On the centre <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and upper left corner of the <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> a parchment fragment from an older manuscript is visible through large gaps in the leather. The <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> has been painted grey at a later date.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1401">15th century</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Origin and early provenance unknown. Purchased by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102557">Bernhard Rosenblad</persName> in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100041">Leipzig</placeName> in <date when="1830"/>. Purchased from him by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102612">G. J. R. Gordon</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased from <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102612">G. J. R. Gordon</persName> by the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">Royal Library</orgName> in <date when="1845"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
                    <msPart>
                        <msIdentifier>
                            <idno type="codicologicalUnit">1</idno>
                        </msIdentifier>
                        <msContents>
                            <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="1ra" to="119vb" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102624"> Nicholas of Lyra </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Commentaries on Matthew and John</title>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="1ra" to="4ra" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Prologue</title>
                                    <incipit>QUatuor facies vni et cetera Ezechiel primo secundum quod scribit beatus gregorius</incipit>
                                    <explicit>uel faciebus significabantur iiii<hi rend="super">or</hi> ewangeliste et sic patet textus</explicit>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="4ra" to="59rb" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Commentary on Matthew</title>
                                    <rubric>capitulum primum</rubric>
                                    <incipit>Liber generacionis ihesu christi Ewangelium mathei diuiditur in d<supplied reason="omitted">uas</supplied> partes </incipit>
                                    <explicit>ut sic non deficiet fides petri Ad laudem et gloriam domini nostri ihesu christi Qui est honor et gloria in secula seculorum AMEN </explicit>
                                    <finalRubric>Explicit Postilla super Matheum Edita a fratre Nycolao de Lyra de ordine fratrum Mynorum deo gracias amen</finalRubric>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="59va" to="61ra" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Prologue</title>
                                    <incipit>FAcies aquile desuper ipsorum quatuor ezechieli id est ezechiel propheta cui aperti</incipit>
                                    <explicit>doctrina quia paratus est reuelare veritatem fideliter inquirentibus ipsam </explicit>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="61ra" to="119vb" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Commentary on John</title>
                                    <rubric>capitulum primum </rubric>
                                    <incipit>IN principio erat verbum sed quod patet ex predictis intencio beati Iohannis est</incipit>
                                    <explicit defective="true">id est audiebat ita quod ibi accipitur uisus pro auditu</explicit>
                                    <note>The text ends in the middle of a gloss on John 20:27. <locus from="120" to="120" scheme="folios"/> is glued to the cover as a pastedown, the text on this leaf seems to consist of random glosses. The first gloss is on Mat. 5:21, further down on Mat. 4:17, followed by undidentified glosses.</note>
                                </msItem>
                                <note>There are no modern editions of these commentaries, but they were included in early prints of the Bible, e.g. <ref target="https://www.digitale-sammlungen.de/en/details/bsb10141270">Lyon 1545</ref>.</note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msContents>
                        <physDesc>
                            <objectDesc>
                                <supportDesc material="parchment">
                                    <support>
                                        <p>
                                            <locus from="1r" to="119v" scheme="folios"/>
                                            <material>Parchment</material>
                                            <dimensions type="leaf">
                                                <height quantity="295" unit="mm"/>
                                                <width quantity="210" unit="mm"/>
                                            </dimensions>
                                        </p>
                                    </support>
                                    <extent>
                                        <measure type="textblockLeaves" quantity="119" unit="folios"/>
                                    </extent>
                                    <foliation>Running titles in red ink. </foliation>
                                    <condition>The parchement is dirty, wrinkled, and torn in places. Holes in the parchment throughout, some of them with contemporary repairs, e.g. on <locus from="99" to="99" scheme="folios"/>. Cuts or tears in the parchment in some places, e.g. in the outer margin on <locus from="42" to="42" scheme="folios"/>. Leaves damaged by damp or spills here and there, especially on <locus from="109" to="118" scheme="folios"/>, where it partially affects the legibility of the text.</condition>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout columns="2" ruledLines="50">
                                        <dimensions type="written">
                                            <height quantity="230" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="160" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                        <note>Ruling and guidelines in ink. Pricking in the margins.</note>
                                    </layout>
                                </layoutDesc>
                            </objectDesc>
                            <handDesc>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-1">Textualis.</handNote>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1vb" to="120ra" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Scattered additions in ink by one or several medieval hands in the margins throughout. The additions consist of notes on the content, corrections, and manicules and nota marks. Throughout there are also notes in small letters in ink and pencil in the running titles. These are probably instructions to the rubricator.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1vb" to="1vb" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>In the lower margin there is a note that refers to <locus from="9rb" to="9rb" scheme="folios"/> for relevant content, on 9rb a note refers back to 1vb.</note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in dark brown ink, capitals touched in red, rubrics in red and with red strike-through.</p>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="1ra" to="1ra" scheme="folios"/>, opening foliate initial Q over 6 lines. Letter in shades of green on gold and framed in pink. Counterspace filled with red and gold. The letter extends into the margins in a vegetative shape with leaves in green, yellow, blue, pink, and gold. <locus from="59va" to="59va" scheme="folios"/>, decorated initial F over 5 lines. The initial is similar to the opening initial, but smaller and without gold, except for in the counterspace. The body is painted in grey and purple, counterspace filled with red and gold, and the leaf shapes in green, blue, and yellow. <locus from="2ra" to="118va" scheme="folios"/>, plain initials over 2-3 lines in red.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote type="images">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="5va" to="5va" scheme="folios"/>, diagram in brown and red ink showing the family tree of King David.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
                        </physDesc>
